---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const features = [
  { href: "/docs/architecture/", title: "Typed runtime", body: "A Rust core that owns turn lifecycle, cancellation, events, tools, policy, and replay invariants." },
  { href: "/docs/extensibility/", title: "Native extensions", body: "Install inference engines, session stores, memory, tools, policy contributors, event sinks, and UI surfaces through one registry." },
  { href: "/docs/providers/", title: "Provider neutral", body: "OpenAI Responses, Anthropic, Gemini, chat-completions-style engines, and mock providers translate into canonical Roder types." },
  { href: "/docs/app-server/", title: "App-server first", body: "The TUI and desktop clients speak to the same local control plane used by automation and external tools." },
  { href: "/docs/tools/", title: "Capability scoped", body: "Tool execution is routed through policy modes, explicit tool specs, approval events, and scoped runtime handles." },
  { href: "/docs/event-bus/", title: "Replayable events", body: "Every meaningful transition is a typed event suitable for UI rendering, journals, telemetry, evals, and RL traces." },
];
---

<Layout title="Roder · Rust-native extensible agent harness">
  <section class="container">
    <div class="hero">
      <div class="hero-copy">
        <div class="eyebrow-line">Rust Coder / extension-first agent infrastructure</div>
        <h1 class="wordmark">Roder</h1>
        <p class="tagline">
          A Rust-native, extension-first harness for coding agents, research systems,
          reinforcement-learning environments, and AI-native developer tools.
        </p>
        <div class="cta-row">
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/docs/">Read the docs</a>
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/contact/">Work with the authors</a>
          <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/docs/install/">Run it locally</a>
          <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/mission/">Mission paper</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <img class="logo" src="/roder-icon.png" alt="Roder icon" />
    </div>

    <div class="feature-strip" aria-label="Roder architecture summary">
      <div class="metric"><strong>Rust</strong><span>typed core and native crates</span></div>
      <div class="metric"><strong>Events</strong><span>replayable runtime stream</span></div>
      <div class="metric"><strong>Extensions</strong><span>providers, tools, stores, sinks</span></div>
      <div class="metric"><strong>Control</strong><span>TUI, app server, desktop clients</span></div>
    </div>

    <pre><code>$ cargo build --workspace
$ cargo test -p roder-cli
$ cargo run -p roder-cli
$ cargo run -p roder-cli -- app-server</code></pre>

    <h2>What Roder is</h2>
    <p>
      Roder is the harness layer underneath coding-agent products. It owns the boring,
      high-stakes parts of an agent runtime: model orchestration, tool execution, policy,
      capability boundaries, context assembly, session persistence, checkpointing, event
      streaming, and replay.
    </p>
    <p>
      The project lives in <code>~/w/gode</code>, but the Rust workspace has been refounded
      around <code>roder-*</code> crates. New work belongs in the Rust crates; the legacy Go
      implementation remains in the repository as a behavioral reference during the rewrite.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Alpha.</strong> Core types, extension traits, commands, protocol methods, and
      config keys are still moving. Treat the roadmap and crate boundaries as the working
      contract until a stable API is declared.
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>For labs and product teams.</strong> The Roder authors work with AI labs
      embedding harnesses into RL fine-tuning infrastructure and with startups building
      agent products on a modifiable Rust runtime.
      <a href="/contact/">Start a conversation</a>.
    </div>

    <h2>Explore</h2>
    <div class="features">
      {features.map((f) => (
        <a class="feature-card" href={f.href}>
          <h3>{f.title}</h3>
          <p>{f.body}</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>

    <h2>Core bet</h2>
    <p>
      Agent systems should not keep rebuilding the same scaffolding around every new model
      API. Roder makes conversations, turns, tool calls, inference events, file changes,
      policy decisions, sessions, and checkpoints canonical Rust concepts. Extensions
      translate into that model; the core keeps the invariants.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>
